<figureCitation id="13E5F495A6F12CACFF17FBB11083FB8A" box="[151,230,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="143.[151,250,1665,1687]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1631]" captionTargetId="figure-162@143.[151,1436,193,1643]" captionTargetPageId="143" captionText="FIGURE 29. Worker caste of Mayaponera constricta: lateral and dorsal view of body and full-face view of head (CASENT0249137, Ryan Perry and www.antweb.org); world distribution of Mayaponera." pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B61E810A6F12CACFF17FB46137FFB4F" blockId="142.[151,794,1184,1206]" box="[151,794,1184,1206]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
Type-species: 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFEA8FB4712E6FB4C" authority="Mayr, 1884: 31" authorityName="Mayr" authorityPageNumber="31" authorityYear="1884" box="[296,643,1184,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="constricta">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFEA8FB4711BBFB4C" box="[296,478,1185,1206]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Ponera constricta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF4F95E1A6F12CACFE64FB4612E6FB4C" author="Mayr, G." box="[484,643,1184,1206]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" pagination="31 - 38" refId="ref155241" refString="Mayr, G. (1884) [Untitled. Descriptions of eight new species.] In: Radoszkowsky, O. Fourmis de Cayenne Francaise. Trudy Russkago Entomologicheskago Obshchestva, 18, 31 - 38." type="journal article" year="1884">Mayr, 1884: 31</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; by monotypy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B61E810A6F12CACFF17FB0511E0FAE5" blockId="142.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFF17FB051143FB00" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; Shattuck" authorityYear="2014" box="[151,294,1251,1274]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mayaponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF17FB051143FB00" box="[151,294,1251,1274]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mayaponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a monotypic genus widespread in Central and South America. It is found in wide range of natural and farming habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3C4BB9BA6F12CACFF47FACC1255FA71" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B61E810A6F12CACFF47FACC1255FA71" blockId="142.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF47FACC1122FAB9" bold="true" box="[199,327,1322,1347]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Etymology</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFED4FACD1186FAB8" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; Shattuck" authorityYear="2014" box="[340,483,1323,1346]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mayaponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFED4FACD1186FAB8" box="[340,483,1323,1346]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mayaponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named in memory of the first author’s daughter Maya and for the Maya peoples of southern 
<collectingCountry id="F3C9A880A6F12CACFF7FFAA81131FA9D" box="[255,340,1358,1383]" name="Mexico" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and northern Central America, included in the range of the genus. The suffix - 
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFB56FAA91540FA9C" box="[1238,1317,1359,1382]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">ponera</emphasis>
is derived from the subfamily name 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFE38FA941249FA71" box="[440,556,1394,1419]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ponerinae">Ponerinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3C4BB9BA6F12CADFF47FA70136CF853" lastPageId="143" lastPageNumber="144" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B61E810A6F12CACFF47FA7010BBF951" blockId="142.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF47FA701124FA55" bold="true" box="[199,321,1430,1455]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFEC9FA7111BDFA54" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; Shattuck" authorityYear="2014" box="[329,472,1431,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mayaponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFEC9FA7111BDFA54" box="[329,472,1431,1454]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mayaponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
workers lack any obvious autapomorphies and superficially have a very generalized appearance. They are most likely to be confused with some 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFCC0FA5D13D8FA28" box="[832,957,1467,1490]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFCC0FA5D13D8FA28" box="[832,957,1467,1490]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Neoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFC75FA5D14E4FA28" box="[1013,1153,1467,1490]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mesoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFC75FA5D14E4FA28" box="[1013,1153,1467,1490]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mesoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFB3CFA5D152EFA28" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; Shattuck" authorityYear="2014" box="[1212,1355,1467,1490]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mayaponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFB3CFA5D152EFA28" box="[1212,1355,1467,1490]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mayaponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFF5AFA391132FA0C" box="[218,343,1503,1526]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF5AFA391132FA0C" box="[218,343,1503,1526]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Neoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its round propodeal spiracles, deeply impressed metanotal groove (at most only slightly impressed in 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFEACF9E511CDF9E0" box="[300,424,1539,1562]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFEACF9E511CDF9E0" box="[300,424,1539,1562]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Neoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and strongly narrowed propodeum with a dorsal longitudinal groove. It can be separated from the handful of 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFEFBF9C11235F9C5" box="[379,592,1574,1599]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFEFBF9C1119DF9C4" box="[379,504,1575,1598]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Neoponera</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in which the propodeal spiracle is round (some members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFAA8F9C115F9F9C5" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1902" box="[1320,1436,1574,1599]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Leptogenys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emiliae">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFAA8F9C115F9F9C5" box="[1320,1436,1574,1599]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">N. emiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group) by the presence of narrow and fang-like metasternal processes (the processes are triangular-shaped in 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFF17F9891176F97C" box="[151,275,1647,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Neoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF17F9891176F97C" box="[151,275,1647,1670]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Neoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFEACF98911DEF97C" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; Shattuck" authorityYear="2014" box="[300,443,1647,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mayaponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFEACF98911DEF97C" box="[300,443,1647,1670]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mayaponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFDD2F98912BBF97C" box="[594,734,1647,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Mesoponera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFDD2F98912BBF97C" box="[594,734,1647,1670]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Mesoponera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a complex metapleural gland orifice and prominent arolia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B61E810A6F12CACFF47F95012BCF815" blockId="142.[151,1437,1250,2031]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFF47F95011A2F935" bold="true" box="[199,455,1718,1743]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Synoptic description.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B9AA3402A6F12CACFE52F950124DF935" box="[466,552,1718,1743]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Worker.</emphasis>
Medium-sized (TL 
<quantity id="4C2645F5A6F12CACFC95F95013E8F935" box="[789,909,1718,1743]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.75" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="6.75" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="6.0">6–7.5 mm</quantity>
) slender ants with the standard characters of 
<taxonomicName id="4CDE9393A6F12CACFF17F93C109FF909" baseAuthorityName="Forel" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[151,250,1754,1779]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ponerini">Ponerini</taxonomicName>
. Mandibles triangular, with about a dozen teeth on the masticatory margin. Clypeus with a broadly convex anterior margin and a subtle median emargination. Frontal lobes of moderate size. Eyes of moderate size, placed anterior of head midline. Metanotal groove deeply impressed. Propodeal dorsum strongly narrowed and with a longitudinal groove. Propodeal spiracles round. Metapleural gland orifice complex, with a posterior U-shaped cuticular lip and a shallow lateral groove. Metatibial spur formula (1s, 1p). Arolia prominent. Petiole a thick scale. Gaster with only a weak girdling constriction between pre- and postsclerites of A4. Stridulitrum present on pretergite of A4. Head and body finely punctate, with scattered pilosity and dense pubescence. Color dark brownish gray. 
<collectingRegion id="491A26F2A6F12CACFEC4F8301108F815" box="[324,365,2006,2031]" country="South Sudan" name="Lakes" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">See</collectingRegion>
also 
<bibRefCitation id="EF4F95E1A6F12CACFE27F83012B0F815" author="Mackay, W. P. &amp; Mackay, E. E." box="[423,725,2006,2031]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" refId="ref152898" refString="Mackay, W. P. &amp; Mackay, E. E. (2010) The systematics and biology of the New World ants of the genus Pachycondyla (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Edwin Mellon Press, Lewiston, 642 pp." type="book" year="2010">Mackay &amp; Mackay (2010)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
